05542nam a22006855i 9780691206998DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20192008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912069987 a10.1515/97806912069982doi  a(DE-B1597)544944  a(OCoLC)1143843687  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE185.93.M6bM26 2008eb 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a305.89607307622221 aMarsh, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGod's Long Summer :bStories of Faith and Civil Rights /cCharles Marsh. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b16 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE TO THE 2008 EDITION -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION. With God on Our Side: Faiths in Conflict -- tCHAPTER ONE. "I'm on My Way, Praise God": Mrs. Hamer's Fight for Freedom -- tCHAPTER TWO. High Priest of the Anti-Civil Rights Movement: The Calling of Sam Bowers -- tCHAPTER THREE. Douglas Hudgins: Theologian of the Closed Society -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Inside Agitator: Ed King's Church Visits -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Cleveland Sellers and the River of No Return -- tCONCLUSION. Clearburning: Fragments of a Reconciling Faith -- tAFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINTERVIEWS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the summer of 1964, the turmoil of the civil rights movement reached its peak in Mississippi, with activists across the political spectrum claiming that God was on their side in the struggle over racial justice. This was the summer when violence against blacks increased at an alarming rate and when the murder of three civil rights workers in Mississippi resulted in national media attention. Charles Marsh takes us back to this place and time, when the lives of activists on all sides of the civil rights issue converged and their images of God clashed. He weaves their voices into a gripping narrative: a Ku Klux Klansman, for example, borrows fiery language from the Bible to link attacks on blacks to his "priestly calling"; a middle-aged woman describes how the Gospel inspired her to rally other African Americans to fight peacefully for their dignity; a SNCC worker tells of harrowing encounters with angry white mobs and his pilgrimage toward a new racial spirituality called Black Power. Through these emotionally charged stories, Marsh invites us to consider the civil rights movement anew, in terms of religion as a powerful yet protean force driving social action. The book's central figures are Fannie Lou Hamer, who "worked for Jesus" in civil rights activism; Sam Bowers, the Imperial Wizard of the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan of Mississippi; William Douglas Hudgins, an influential white Baptist pastor and unofficial theologian of the "closed society"; Ed King, a white Methodist minister and Mississippi native who campaigned to integrate Protestant congregations; and Cleveland Sellers, a SNCC staff member turned black militant. Marsh focuses on the events and religious convictions that led each person into the political upheaval of 1964. He presents an unforgettable American social landscape, one that is by turns shameful and inspiring. In conclusion, Marsh suggests that it may be possible to sift among these narratives and lay the groundwork for a new thinking about racial reconciliation and the beloved community. He maintains that the person who embraces faith's life-affirming energies will leave behind a most powerful legacy of social activism and compassion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszMississippixHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movements